# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: allium-validum
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:allium-validum/acuminate] The following terms are used to describe leaf morphology in the description and taxonomy of plants.
[src:allium-validum/acuminate] Leaves may be simple (that is, the leaf blade or 'lamina' is undivided) or compound (that is, the leaf blade is divided into two or more leaflets).
[src:allium-validum/acuminate] The edge of the leaf may be regular or irregular, and may be smooth or have hair, bristles, or spines.
[src:allium-validum/acuminate] For more terms describing other aspects of leaves besides their overall morphology, see the leaf article.
[src:allium-validum/acuminate] The terms listed here all are supported by technical and professional usage, but they cannot be represented as mandatory or undebatable; readers must use their judgement.
[src:allium-validum/acuminate] For example, whether to call leaves on the same tree "acuminate", "lanceolate", or "linear" could depend on individual judgement, or which part of the tree one collected them from.
[src:allium-validum/acuminate] The same cautions might apply to "caudate", "cuspidate", and "mucronate", or to "crenate", "dentate", and "serrate".
[src:allium-validum/acuminate] Another problem is to establish definitions that meet all cases or satisfy all authorities and readers.
[src:allium-validum/acuminate] Various authors or field workers might come to incompatible conclusions, or might try to compromise by qualifying terms so vaguely that a description of a particular plant practically loses its value.
[src:allium-validum/acuminate] Use of these terms is not restricted to leaves, but may be applied to morphology of other parts of plants, e.g. bracts, bracteoles, stipules, sepals, petals, carpels or scales.
[src:allium-validum/acuminate] Some of these terms are also used for similar-looking anatomical features on animals.
[src:allium-validum/acuminate] Leaves of most plants include a flat structure called the blade or lamina supported by a network of veins, a petiole and a leaf base; but not all leaves are flat, some are cylindrical.
[src:allium-validum/acuminate] Leaves may be simple, with a single leaf blade, or compound, with several leaflets.
[src:allium-validum/acuminate] Compound leaves may be pinnate with pinnae (leaflets) on both sides of a rachis (axis), or may be palmate with multiple leaflets arising from a single point.
[src:allium-validum/acuminate] Being one of the more visible features, leaf shape is commonly used for plant identification.
[src:allium-validum/acuminate] Similar terms are used for other plant parts, such as petals, tepals, and bracts.
[src:allium-validum/acuminate] Leaf margins (edges) are frequently used in visual plant identification because they are usually consistent within a species or group of species, and are an easy characteristic to observe.
[src:allium-validum/acuminate] Edge and margin are interchangeable in the sense that they both refer to the outside perimeter of a leaf.
[src:allium-validum/acuminate] Leaves may also be folded, sculpted or rolled in various ways.
[src:allium-validum/acuminate] If the leaves are initially folded in the bud, but later unrolls it is called vernation, ptyxis is the folding of an individual leaf in a bud.
[src:allium-validum/acuminate] The Latin word for 'leaf', *folium*, is neuter.
[src:allium-validum/acuminate] In descriptions of a single leaf, the neuter singular ending of the adjective is used, e.g.
[src:allium-validum/acuminate] *folium lanceolatum* 'lanceolate leaf', *folium lineare* 'linear leaf'.
[src:allium-validum/acuminate] In descriptions of multiple leaves, the neuter plural is used, e.g.
[src:allium-validum/acuminate] Descriptions commonly refer to the plant using the ablative singular or plural, e.g.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] It is popular throughout West Africa, and goes by many names including **apio**, **ogoglo**, **ogogoro** (**Ogog'**), **VC10,** **Kill Me Quick**, **Efie Nipa, Kele, Kumepreko, Anferewoase, Apiatiti, Home Boy, Nana Drobo, One Touch** among others.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] It is also known as sapele water, kparaga, kai-kai, Sun gbalaja, egun inu igo meaning *The Masquerade in the Bottle*, push-me-push-you, and/or crim-kena, sonsé ("do you do it?" in Yoruba language).
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] In the Igbo language it is known as *Akpuru achia*.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] Other Nigerian epithets include: *Udi Ogagan*, *Agbagba* Urhobo, as well *OHMS* (Our Home Made Stuff), *Iced Water*, *Push Me, I Push You* and *Craze man in the bottle*.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] Ghanaian moonshine is referred to as akpeteshie.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] With British colonization of what became known as the Gold Coast, such local brewing was outlawed in the early 1930s.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] Dotse about his life under British colonial rule: "Our contention was that the drink the white man brought is the same as ours.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] The white men's contention was that ours was too strong...Before the white men came we were using akpeteshie.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] But when they came they banned it, probably because they wanted to make sales on their own liquor.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] When you had a visitor whom you knew very well, then you ordered that kpótomenui be brought.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] The name "akpeteshie" was given to the drink with its prohibition: the word comes from the Ga language (*ape te shie*, the act of hiding) spoken in greater Accra and means *they are hiding*, referring to the secretive way in which non-European inhabitants were forced to consume the beverage.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] Despite being outlawed, illicit spirits remained commonplace, with reports that even schoolboys were able to easily obtain akpeteshie through the 1930s.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] Demand for akpeteshie and the profits to be made from its sale was enough to encourage the spread of sugar cane cultivation in the Anlo region of Ghana.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] Distillation was legalized with decolonization and Ghanaian independence.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] The first factory was established in the Volta Region, taking advantage of the area's supply of sugar cane plantations.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] Ogogoro is distilled from the juice of Raffia palm trees.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] An incision is made in the trunk and a gourd placed outside it for collection, which is collected a day or two later.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] After extraction, the sap is boiled to form steam, which subsequently condenses and is collected for consumption.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] Akpeteshie is distilled from palm wine or sugarcane juice.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] This sweetened liquid or wine is first fermented in a large barrels, sometimes with the help of yeast.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] After this first stage of fermentation, fires are built under the barrels in order to bring the liquid to a boil and pass the resulting vapor through a copper pipe within cooling barrels, where it condenses and drips into sieved jars.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] The boiled juice then undergoes a distillation.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] The resulting spirit is between 40 and 50% alcohol by volume.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] Akpeteshie is not professionally bottled or sealed, but instead poured into unlabeled used bottles.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] The spirit can be bought wholesale from a brewer or by the glass at boutiques and bars.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] Although not professionally advertised, the drink is very popular.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] This is partially due to its price, which is lower than that of other professionally bottled or imported drinks.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] Its relative cheapness makes it a drink associated more with the poor, but even those who can afford better quality are said to consume the spirit in secret.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] The potency of the liquor heavily affects the bodily senses, providing a feeling likened to that of a knockout punch.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] Practiced drinkers can be seen acknowledging receipt by blowing out air or pounding their chest.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] As drink and commodity, respectively, ogogoro carries substantial cultural and economic significance within Nigeria.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] It is an essential part of numerous religious and social ceremonies; Burutu (Ijaw) priests pour it onto the ground as offerings to contact their gods, while fathers of Nigerian brides use it as a libation by which they provide their official blessing to a wedding.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] The economic facets of ogogoro have been equally salient throughout recent Nigerian history.
[src:allium-validum/akpeteshie] Many poor Nigerian families homebrew the drink as a means of economic subsistence, many of whom sell shots of it on city street corners.
[src:allium-validum/alibag-white-onion] Under its Geographical Indication tag, it is referred to as "Alibag White onion".
[src:allium-validum/alibag-white-onion] Alibag White onion is a prized, native vegetable crop in Alibag and so named after it.
[src:allium-validum/alibag-white-onion] It is known locally as "Alibag Pandhara Kanda" (अलिबाग पांढरा कांदा).
[src:allium-validum/alibag-white-onion] The word "Pandhara" refers to the white colour while "Kanda" means onion in the local state language of Marathi.
[src:allium-validum/alibag-white-onion] It was awarded the Geographical Indication (GI) status tag from the Geographical Indications Registry, under the Union Government of India, on 16 November 2022.
[src:allium-validum/alibag-white-onion] Alibag Pandhara Kanda Shetkari Utpadak Gat from Alibag, proposed the GI registration of Alibag White onion.
[src:allium-validum/alibag-white-onion] After filing the application in January 2020, the Onion was granted the GI tag in 2022 by the Geographical Indication Registry in Chennai, making the name "Alibag White onion" exclusive to the Onion grown in the region.
[src:allium-validum/alibag-white-onion] It thus became the second onion variety from Maharashtra after Lasalgaon onion and the 34th type of goods from Maharashtra to earn the GI tag.
[src:allium-validum/alibag-white-onion] The GI tag protects the onion from illegal selling and marketing, and gives it legal protection and a unique identity.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] Currently, *Allanblackia* seeds are harvested in the wild to produce the oil, but these producers cannot produce enough oil to meet market demand.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] Finding sustainable ways to increase production could bring many social, environmental, and economic benefits to the communities which produce *Allanblackia*.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] To ensure increased production is sustainable and benefits the communities growing the trees, a number of organizations have collaborated to develop a set of standards and methods as guidelines for increasing *Allanblackia* production.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] Other organizations are working to establish tree nurseries and other sustainable means of domesticating *Allanblackia*.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] Allanblackia oil is an edible vegetable oil derived from the seeds from the fruits of *Allanblackia* trees.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] This is an evergreen tree producing big brown fruits.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] Inside those fruits are the seeds that contain the allanblackia oil.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] The genus *Allanblackia*, which belongs to the family Clusiaceae, consists of nine (possibly ten) tree species, all restricted to Africa.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] All members of the genus are dioecious (having separate male and female trees).
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] There are nine published species of *Allanblackia*, mostly very similar to each other.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] *Allanblackia* trees are commonly found in the wet tropical rain belt of West, Central and East Africa (from Sierra Leone to Tanzania).
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] They grow primarily in tropical rainforests, but can also be found on cultivated farmland areas.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] These species occur in moist low-land areas (*A. parviflora*, *A. floribunda*) or upland rain forests (*A. stuhlmannii*).
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] The genus *Allanblackia* was named in honour of the botanist Allan Black.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] He was the first curator of Kew Gardens and was responsible for the private collection of Charles Darwin.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] Very respected amongst his peers, he died at a young age aboard ship off the Cocos Islands in the Bay of Bengal and the genus *Allanblackia* was named in his memory.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] The name of *Allanblackia* trees used by the indigenous people in Tanzania is actually *msambu* or *mkimbo* in Swahili or sometimes *mkani* (*mkanyi*, *mkany*) in local languages.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] In Nigeria area of River State the local name used is *obiobo obo*.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] A key characteristic is that the fatty acids are organized into a two main triglycerides.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] These are called 1,3-distearoyl-2-oleoyl-glycerol (abbreviated as SOS at an average level of 69%) and 1,2-dioleoyl-3-stearoyl-sn-glycerol (abbreviated as sn-SOO at an average level of 23%).
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] This simple triglyceride composition provides *Allanblackia* seed oil with very steep melting behavior.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] This composition makes it useful for making food products such as margarine, without any further modification like fractionation of fractional crystallization.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] Specific physical characteristics of SOS-SOO mixtures, like fat crystallization aspects, have extensively been investigated in model systems.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] The volumes of Allanblackia seeds, and hence seed oil, produced until now very low.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] The volume of allanblackia seed oil is in the range of 100 metric tonnes per annum only.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] These volumes are generated by wild-harvesting mainly done by collectors in Tanzania.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] When initial studies on the potential of wild-harvesting were done in the early 2000s, the expectations were very high predicting annual production of up to 40,000 tonnes of seeds.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] In reality only a few tonnes of seeds were harvested in the first year as the number of wild Allanblackia trees that could actually be harvested had severely been overestimated.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] Through the plantation of the tree with local farmers in Tanzania, Ghana and Nigeria, the production volumes are expected to increase in the coming decade, once these trees are old enough to starting producing fruits and big enough to carry more of the large fruit pods.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] Increasing the volumes obviously must be done sustainably and hence socio-economic and environmental aspects are being looked at.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] For example, the value of Allanblackia as a new cash (annual) crop for Africa means training of local communities not to cut Allanblackia trees for use as timber and firewood.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] But doing so is also a means of helping to conserve local biodiversity.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] The Union for Ethical Biotrade (UEBT) has developed a standard and a verification framework against which the sustainability of the Allanblackia supply chain can be audited and approved.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] UEBT is a member of the International Social and Environmental Accreditation and Labelling Alliance, which promotes sustainability standards.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] Wild harvesting as a production method is limited because there are not enough trees to satisfy demand and Allanblackia's flowering and fruiting behavior is erratic.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] Since 2006, Novel Development Tanzania has been involved in a domestication program together with the World Agroforestry Centre to domesticate the species using participatory tree domestication approach.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] The program includes community sensitization, exploration, participatory selections of superior mother trees, conservation in field gene banks, development of agroforestry systems with Allanblackia and market development.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] Secondly, the program consists of developing asexual and sexual propagation protocols, which are necessary to overcome challenges in multiplication such as seed dormancy, long juvenile phase and high variability of desired traits.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] The domestication program of Allanblackia through public-private partnership and participatory tree domestication could serve as a model for domestication of other underutilized African tree species of high economic potential.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] In Tanzania the use of allanblackia seed oil goes back almost a century.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] It has been reported that during the First World War allanblackia oil was already tested as a cocoa butter alternative.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] Also in the seventies the such application was again explored in Europe.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] However the application never hit the market because larger volumes of the oil were simply not available due to the lack of an organized supply chain.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] Nowadays there is still in hardly any local use of Allanblackia seed oil as people prefer use of easily available liquid oils and cheap industrial soaps.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] The allanblackia tree has predominantly been used for timber in the last decades and hence the number of trees has significantly reduced .
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] Most of the allanblackia trees nowadays remaining in the wild are growing in the East Usambara Mountains which provides the right climate for this tree.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] As a result, even today the volumes of oil available from wild-harvesting are still very small.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] The major application potential identified today is in the use as a structuring fat to produce low-trans margarines and dairy cream alternatives, and as cocoa butter equivalent in confectionery applications.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] In the European Union as of December 2014, all different types of vegetable oils will be listed on the ingredient label of food products using those ingredients.
[src:allium-validum/allanblackia-oil] Recently Allanblackia seed oil was introduced in margarine and can be found as such on the product ingredient list.
[src:allium-validum/allicin] Allicin is an oily, slightly yellow liquid that gives garlic its distinctive odor.
[src:allium-validum/allicin] It is also known as allyl thiosulfinate.
[src:allium-validum/allicin] Its biological activity can be attributed to both its antioxidant activity and its reaction with thiol-containing proteins.
[src:allium-validum/allicin] Allicin features the thiosulfinate functional group, R-S(O)-S-R.
[src:allium-validum/allicin] The compound is not present in garlic unless tissue damage occurs, and is formed by the action of the enzyme alliinase on alliin.
[src:allium-validum/allicin] Allicin is chiral but occurs naturally only as a racemate.
[src:allium-validum/allicin] Alliinase is irreversibly deactivated below pH 3; as such, allicin is generally not produced in the body from the consumption of fresh or powdered garlic.
[src:allium-validum/allicin] Furthermore, allicin can be unstable, breaking down within 16 hours at 23 °C.
[src:allium-validum/allicin] The biosynthesis of allicin commences with the conversion of cysteine into *S*-allyl-L-cysteine.
[src:allium-validum/allicin] Oxidation of this thioether gives the sulfoxide (alliin).
[src:allium-validum/allicin] The enzyme alliinase, which contains pyridoxal phosphate (PLP), cleaves alliin, generating allylsulfenic acid (CH2=CHCH2SOH), pyruvate, and ammonium ions.
[src:allium-validum/allicin] At room temperature, two molecules of allylsulfenic acid condense to form allicin.
[src:allium-validum/allicin] Allicin has been studied for its potential to treat various kinds of multiple drug resistance bacterial infections, as well as viral and fungal infections in vitro, but as of 2016, the safety and efficacy of allicin to treat infections in people was unclear.
[src:allium-validum/allicin] A Cochrane review found there to be insufficient clinical evidence regarding the effects of allicin in preventing or treating common cold.
[src:allium-validum/allicin] It was first isolated and studied in the laboratory by Chester J.
[src:allium-validum/allicin] Allicin was discovered as part of efforts to create thiamine derivatives in the 1940s, mainly in Japan.
[src:allium-validum/allicin] Allicin became a model for medicinal chemistry efforts to create other thiamine disulfides.
[src:allium-validum/allicin] The results included sulbutiamine, fursultiamine (thiamine tetrahydrofurfuryl disulfide) and benfothiamine.
[src:allium-validum/allicin] These compounds are hydrophobic, easily pass from the intestines to the bloodstream, and are reduced to thiamine by cysteine or glutathione.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] The subfamily contains both well-known garden plants and weeds, such as *Nothoscordum*.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] When Linnaeus formerly described the type genus *Allium* in his *Species Plantarum* in 1753, thirty species had this name.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] He placed *Allium* in a grouping he referred to as *Hexandria monogynia* (i.e. six stamens and one pistil) containing 51 genera in all.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] In 1763, Michel Adanson, who proposed the concept of families of plants, included *Allium* and related genera as a grouping within Liliaceae as Section IV, *Les Oignons* (Onions), or *Cepae* in Latin.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] De Jussieu is officially recognised as the first formal establishment of the suprageneric grouping into families (Ordo) in 1789.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] In this system *Allium* was one of fourteen genera in Ordo VI, *Asphodeles* (Asphodeli), of the third class (*Stamina epigyna*) of Monocots.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] In 1786, the Allioideae were first described by their type genus as Alliaceae by Batsch.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] In 1797, after the appearance of the Jussieu system, this was validated by Borkhausen.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Jean Henri Jaume Saint-Hilaire (1805), who developed the concept of Amaryllidaceae, continued Jussieu's treatment of *Allium* under Asphodeli (which he considered synonymous with Adanson's Liliaceae and Jussieu's Asphodeli).
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] He placed *Allium* in an unnamed monotypic section of Asphodeli defined as *Fleurs en ombelle, racine bulbeuse.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Calice à six parties egales* (umbellate flowers, bulbous, calyx of six equal parts).
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Subsequently, de Candolle reverted the family name back to Liliaceae from Asphodeli.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] He divided the Liliaceae into a series of Ordres, and the second ordre was named *Asphodèles*, based on Jussieus' family of that name, in which he placed *Allium*.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] The term 'Alliaceae' then reappeared in its subfamilial form, Allieae, in Dumortier's *Florula Belgica* (1827), with six genera.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] The 'Alliaceae' have been treated as Allieae within the family Liliaceae (or Aspholecaceae, a partial synonym) by most authorities since.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] In 1830, Lindley, the first English systematist, considered Alliaceae to be part of the tribe Asphodeleae, separating them from the Liliaceae as he understood them.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] He also described the closely related Gilliesieae (p.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] 274), which with the Allieae would later migrate to Amaryllidaceae.By the time of his final work in 1846 he realised that the Liliaceae, which had expanded greatly were very diverse in circumscription with many subdivisions, and were already paraphyletic ("catch-all").
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] He absorbed Asphodeleae into this family and created a suborder of Scilleae, which he considered equivalent to Link's Allieae.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] By the time of the next major British (though written in Latin) classification, that of Bentham and Hooker (1883), the Allieae had become one of 20 tribes within Liliaceae.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] The Allieae included Lindley's Gilliesieae as one of its four subtribes.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Similarly in the German language literature, Engler's classification (1903) treated Allieae and Gilliesiae as tribes of subfamily Allioideae, within Liliaceae.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] In the early 20th century, doubts were expressed about the placement of the alliaceous genera within Liliaceae, based solely on the position of the ovary.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Lotsy was the first taxonomist to propose separating them, and in his system he describes Alliaceae and Gilliesiaceae as new and separate families from Liliaceae (1911).
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] This approach was later adopted by a number of other authorities, such as Dahlgren (1985) and Rahn (1998).
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] In 1926, John Hutchinson moved the tribes Allieae and Gilliesieaes from Liliaceae to the Amaryllidaceae, although this was not universally adopted.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Thus, Allieae were variously treated as either Liliaceae, Amaryllidaceae, or Alliaceae.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Further examination of the heterogeneity of the Liliaceae by Huber (1969) supported the removal of these two tribes, into Alliaceae and this family was treated as an independent entity from then onwards with the exception of Cronquist who reverted to a very broad concept of Liliaceae.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] They divided Alliaceae into three subfamilies: Agapanthoideae, Allioideae, and Gilliesioideae.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Agapanthoideae consisted of two genera (*Agapanthus* and *Tulbaghia*).
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Allioideae contained two tribes, Brodiaeeae (ten genera) and a broadly defined Allieae, which they considered distinct enough to alternatively consider as subfamilies in their own right.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Gilliesioideae was composed of about half of the genera now placed in Gilliesieae, the rest being assigned to Allieae.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] In 1996, a molecular phylogenetic study of the*rbcL* gene showed that *Agapanthus* was misplaced in Alliaceae, and the authors excluded it from the family.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] They also raised Brodiaeeae to family rank as Themidaceae.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] They reduced the tribe Allieae to two genera, *Allium* and *Milula*, and transferred the rest of Allieae to Gilliesieae.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] This is the circumscription which the Angiosperm Phylogeny Group accepted in the APG classification of 1998 and which later became known as Alliaceae *sensu stricto*.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] In the APG II system of 2003, Alliaceae could be recognized *sensu stricto* or *sensu lato*, as mentioned above.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Soon after the publication of APG II, the ICBN conserved the name Amaryllidaceae for the family that had been called Alliaceae *sensu lato* in APG II.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] When the APG III system was published in 2009, the alternative circumscriptions were discontinued and Alliaceae was no longer recognized.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Alliaceae *sensu stricto* became the subfamily Allioideae of Amaryllidaceae *sensu lato*.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Some botanists have not strictly followed the Angiosperm Phylogeny Group and have recognized the smaller version of Alliaceae at family rank.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Successive revisions of the Angiosperm Phylogeny Group (APG) classification have changed the circumscription of the family.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Quite a few of the plants that were once included in family Alliaceae have been assigned to the subfamily Brodiaeoideae (rather than the subfamily Allioideae).
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] The largest genera are *Allium* (260–690 species), *Nothoscordum* (25), and *Tulbaghia* (22).
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Some of the generic limits are not clear.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] *Ipheion*, *Nothoscordum*, and possibly others are not monophyletic.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Allioideae is divided into four tribes: Allieae, Tulbaghieae, Gilliesieae and Leucocoryneae.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] The first three correspond to the three subfamilies under the older family Alliaceae (Alliodiae, Tulbaghioideae and Gilliesioideae).
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Leucocoryneae was added in 2014 by dividing Gilliesieae into two separate tribes, corresponding to the original tribes within Gilliesioideae, elevating Iphiae *nom. nud.* to tribe Leucocoryneae.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Allieae contains only one genus *Allium* (*Milula* is merged with *Allium* in the latest systems).
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Tulbaghieae contains two genera, *Tulbaghia* and *Prototulbaghia*.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Gilliesieae and Leucocoryneae contain the remaining fifteen genera.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Allieae is sister to a clade composed of Tulbaghieae and Gilliesieae.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] It is characterised by simple or prolific bulbs, sometimes with lateral rhizomes.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Leaf sheaths are long, tepals are free and the corona is absent.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] The style is positioned apical relative to the ovary.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] The ovary usually has two, four or numerous ovules per locule in two longitudinal rows.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] It has one genus, *Allium*, and over 500 species.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] It is distributed over all the Northern hemisphere.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Characterised by simple or prolific bulbs, sometimes with lateral rhizomes.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Leaf sheaths long, tepals more or less fused and corona absent.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Ovary usually has two ovules per locule, side by side.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Floral symmetry zygomorphic, septal nectaries absent.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Floral symmetry actinomorphic, septal nectaries present.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Six genera and 42 species, and endemic to South America with the exception of two species of *Nothoscordum*.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Characterised by corm-shaped bulb or rhizome.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Flowers possess a corona, pseudocorona or a fleshy perigonal ring.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] The genera *Androstephium*, *Bessera*, *Bloomeria*, *Brodiaea*, *Dandya*, *Dichelostemma*, *Jaimehintonia*, *Milla*, *Muilla*, *Petronymphe*, *Triteleia*, and *Triteleiopsis* are now treated in the family Themidaceae (alt.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] *Petronymphe* has been restored to Themidaceae from Anthericaceae (now a segregate of Agavaceae).
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] *Latace* Phil. is included in *Nothoscordum*.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Thus, fourteen of the total of 18 genera are endemic to temperate South America.
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Some of the species of *Allium* are important food plants for example onions (*Allium cepa*), chives (*A. schoenoprasum*), garlic (*A. sativum* and *A. scordoprasum*), and leeks (*A. porrum*).
[src:allium-validum/allioideae] Species of *Allium, Gilliesia, Ipheion, Leucocoryne, Nothoscordum*, and *Tulbaghia* are cultivated as ornamentals.
[src:allium-validum/allium-validum] The *Allium validum* bulb is three to five centimeters long, ovoid and clustered on the short end.
[src:allium-validum/allium-validum] The outer coat of the stout rhizome is brown or gray in color, fibrous, and vertically lined.
[src:allium-validum/allium-validum] The stem is 50 to 100 centimeters long and angled.
[src:allium-validum/allium-validum] There are three to six leaves more or less equal to the stem and the leaves are flat or more or less keeled.
[src:allium-validum/allium-validum] There are 15 to 40 flowers with pedicels being seven to twelve millimeters in length.
[src:allium-validum/allium-validum] The flower itself is six to ten millimeters, its perianth parts are more or less erect, narrowly lanceolate, acuminate, and are a rose to white color.
[src:allium-validum/allium-validum] The stamens are longer than the tepals, and there is no ovary crest.
[src:allium-validum/allium-validum] This is a common plant in California, often found in wet meadows at elevations of 1,200 to 3,400 meters (3,900 to 11,200 ft).
[src:allium-validum/allium-validum] *A. validum* prefers sandy and loamy soils and requires well-drained soil.
[src:allium-validum/allium-validum] The plant will grow in acid, basic, or alkaline soils, but only in areas with plenty of moisture and sun.
[src:allium-validum/allium-validum] The bulb *A. validum* can be used as a flavoring for soups and stews although it is somewhat fibrous.
[src:allium-validum/allium-validum] The leaves can be eaten raw or cooked and the flowers can be used as garnish on salads.
[src:allium-validum/allium-validum] It can also be used as a moth repellent.
[src:allium-validum/allium-validum] The whole plant is said to repel insects and moles.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Carl Linnaeus first described the genus *Allium* in 1753.
[src:allium-validum/allium] The generic name *Allium* is the Latin word for garlic, and the type species for the genus is *Allium sativum* which means "cultivated garlic".
[src:allium-validum/allium] The decision to include a species in the genus *Allium* is taxonomically difficult, and species boundaries are unclear.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Estimates of the number of species are as low as 260, and as high as 979.
[src:allium-validum/allium] In the APG III classification system, *Allium* is placed in the family Amaryllidaceae, subfamily Allioideae (formerly the family Alliaceae).
[src:allium-validum/allium] In some of the older classification systems, *Allium* was placed in Liliaceae.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Molecular phylogenetic studies have shown this circumscription of Liliaceae is not monophyletic.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Various *Allium* species have been cultivated from the earliest times.
[src:allium-validum/allium] About a dozen species are economically important as crops, or garden vegetables, and an increasing number of species are important as ornamental plants.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Plants belonging to this genus produce cysteine-derived organosulfur compounds, which impart a distinctive onion or garlic flavor and scent.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Many are used as food plants, though not all members of the genus are equally flavorful.
[src:allium-validum/allium] In most cases, both bulb and leaves are edible.
[src:allium-validum/allium] The characteristic *Allium* flavor depends on the sulfate content of the soil the plant grows in.
[src:allium-validum/allium] In the rare occurrence of sulfur-depleted growth conditions, all *Allium* species completely lose their usual odors and flavors.
[src:allium-validum/allium] The genus *Allium* (alliums) is characterised by herbaceous geophyte perennials with true bulbs, some of which are borne on rhizomes, and an onion or garlic odor and flavor.
[src:allium-validum/allium] The bulbs are solitary or clustered and tunicate and the plants are perennialized by the bulbs reforming annually from the base of the old bulbs, or are produced on the ends of rhizomes or, in a few species, at the ends of stolons.
[src:allium-validum/allium] A small number of species have tuberous roots.
[src:allium-validum/allium] The bulbs' outer coats are commonly brown or grey, with a smooth texture, and are fibrous, or with cellular reticulation.
[src:allium-validum/allium] The inner coats of the bulbs are membranous.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Many alliums have basal leaves that commonly wither away from the tips downward before or while the plants flower, but some species have persistent foliage.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Plants produce from one to 12 leaves, most species having linear, channeled or flat leaf blades.
[src:allium-validum/allium] The leaf blades are straight or variously coiled, but some species have broad leaves, including *A. victorialis* and *A. tricoccum*.
[src:allium-validum/allium] The leaves are sessile, and very rarely narrowed into a petiole.
[src:allium-validum/allium] The flowers, which are produced on scapes are erect or in some species pendent, having six petal-like tepals produced in two whorls.
[src:allium-validum/allium] The flowers have one style and six epipetalous stamens; the anthers and pollen can vary in color depending on the species.
[src:allium-validum/allium] The ovaries are superior, and three-lobed with three locules.
[src:allium-validum/allium] The fruits are capsules that open longitudinally along the capsule wall between the partitions of the locule.
[src:allium-validum/allium] The seeds are black, and have a rounded shape.
[src:allium-validum/allium] The terete or flattened flowering scapes are normally persistent.
[src:allium-validum/allium] The inflorescences are umbels, in which the outside flowers bloom first and flowering progresses to the inside.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Some species produce bulbils within the umbels, and in some species, such as *Allium paradoxum*, the bulbils replace some or all the flowers.
[src:allium-validum/allium] The umbels are subtended by noticeable spathe bracts, which are commonly fused and normally have around three veins.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Some bulbous alliums increase by forming little bulbs or "offsets" around the old one, as well as by seed.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Several species can form many bulbils in the flowerhead; in the so-called "tree onion" or Egyptian onion (*A.* × *proliferum*) the bulbils are few, but large enough to be pickled.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Many of the species of *Allium* have been used as food items throughout their ranges.
[src:allium-validum/allium] There are several unrelated species that are somewhat similar in appearance to alliums but are poisonous (e.g. in North America, death camas, *Toxicoscordion venenosum*), but none of these has the distinctive scent of onions or garlic.
[src:allium-validum/allium] With over 850 to 1,000 species *Allium* is the sole genus in the Allieae, one of four tribes of subfamily Allioideae (Amaryllidaceae).
[src:allium-validum/allium] New species continue to be described and *Allium* is one of the largest monocotyledonous genera, but the precise taxonomy of *Allium* is poorly understood, with incorrect descriptions being widespread.
[src:allium-validum/allium] The difficulties arise from the fact that the genus displays considerable polymorphism and has adapted to a wide variety of habitats.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Furthermore, traditional classifications had been based on homoplasious characteristics (the independent evolution of similar features in species of different lineages).
[src:allium-validum/allium] However, the genus has been shown to be monophyletic, containing three major clades, although some proposed subgenera are not.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Some progress is being made using molecular phylogenetic methods, and the internal transcribed spacer (ITS) region, including the 5.8S rDNA and the two spacers ITS1 and ITS2, is one of the more commonly used markers in the study of the differentiation of the *Allium* species.
[src:allium-validum/allium] When Linnaeus formerly described the genus *Allium* in his *Species Plantarum* (1753), there were thirty species with this name.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Linnaeus originally grouped his 30 species into three alliances, e.g.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Since then, many attempts have been made to divide the growing number of recognised species into infrageneric subgroupings, initially as sections, and then as subgenera further divided into sections.
[src:allium-validum/allium] The modern era of phylogenetic analysis dates to 1996.
[src:allium-validum/allium] In 2006 Friesen, Fritsch, and Blattner described a new classification with 15 subgenera, 56 sections, and about 780 species based on the nuclear ribosomal gene internal transcribed spacers.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Some of the subgenera correspond to the once separate genera (*Caloscordum*, *Milula*, *Nectaroscordum*) included in the Gilliesieae.
[src:allium-validum/allium] The terminology has varied with some authors subdividing subgenera into Sections and others Alliances.
[src:allium-validum/allium] The term Alliance has also been used for subgroupings within species, e.g.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Subsequent molecular phylogenetic studies have shown the 2006 classification is a considerable improvement over previous classifications, but some of its subgenera and sections are probably not monophyletic.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Meanwhile, the number of new species continued to increase, reaching 800 by 2009, and the pace of discovery has not decreased.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Detailed studies have focused on a number of subgenera, including *Amerallium*.
[src:allium-validum/allium] *Amerallium* is strongly supported as monophyletic.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Subgenus *Melanocrommyum* has also been the subject of considerable study , while work on subgenus *Allium* has focussed on section *Allium*, including *Allium ampeloprasum*, although sampling was not sufficient to test the monophyly of the section.
[src:allium-validum/allium] The major evolutionary lineages or lines correspond to the three major clades.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Line one (the oldest) with three subgenera is predominantly bulbous, the second, with five subgenera and the third with seven subgenera contain both bulbous and rhizomatous taxa.
[src:allium-validum/allium] The three evolutionary lineages and 15 subgenera here represent the classification schemes of Friesen et al.
[src:allium-validum/allium] (2006) and Li (2010), and subsequent additional species and revisions.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Although this lineage consists of three subgenera, nearly all the species are attributed to subgenus *Amerallium*, the third largest subgenus of *Allium*.
[src:allium-validum/allium] The lineage is considered to represent the most ancient line within *Allium*, and to be the only lineage that is purely bulbous, the other two having both bulbous and rhizomatous taxa.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Within the lineage *Amerallium* is a sister group to the other two subgenera (*Microscordum*+*Nectaroscordum*).
[src:allium-validum/allium] Nearly all the species in this lineage of five subgenera are accounted for by subgenus *Melanocrommyum*, which is most closely associated with subgenera *Vvedenskya* and *Porphyroprason*, phylogenetically.
[src:allium-validum/allium] These three genera are late-branching whereas the remaining two subgenera, *Caloscordum* and *Anguinum*, are early branching.
[src:allium-validum/allium] The third evolutionary line contains the greatest number of sections (seven), and also the largest subgenus of the genus *Allium*: subgenus *Allium*, which includes the type species of the genus, *Allium sativum*.
[src:allium-validum/allium] This subgenus also contains the majority of the species in its lineage.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Within the lineage, the phylogeny is complex.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Two small subgenera, *Butomissa* and *Cyathophora* form a sister clade to the remaining five subgenera, with *Butomissa* as the first branching group.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Amongst the remaining five subgenera, *Rhizirideum* forms a medium-sized subgenus that is the sister to the other four, larger, subgenera.
[src:allium-validum/allium] The majority of *Allium* species are native to the Northern Hemisphere, being spread throughout the holarctic region, from dry subtropics to the boreal zone, predominantly in Asia.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Of the latter, 138 species occur in China, about a sixth of all *Allium* species, representing five subgenera.
[src:allium-validum/allium] A few species are native to Africa and Central and South America.
[src:allium-validum/allium] A single known exception, *Allium dregeanum* occurs in the Southern Hemisphere (South Africa).
[src:allium-validum/allium] There are two centres of diversity, a major one from the Mediterranean Basin to Central Asia and Pakistan, while a minor one is found in western North America.
[src:allium-validum/allium] The genus is especially diverse in the eastern Mediterranean.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Species grow in various conditions from dry, well-drained mineral-based soils to moist, organic soils; most grow in sunny locations, but a number also grow in forests (e.g., *A. ursinum*), or even in swamps or water.
[src:allium-validum/allium] The genus *Allium* has very large variation between species in their genome size that is not accompanied by changes in ploidy level.
[src:allium-validum/allium] This remarkable variation was noted in the discussion of the evolution of junk DNA and resulted in the Onion Test, a "reality check for anyone who thinks they have come up with a universal function for junk DNA".
[src:allium-validum/allium] Genome sizes vary between 7.5 Gb in *A. schoenoprasum* and 30.9 Gb in *A. ursinum*, both of which are diploid.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Many *Allium* species have been harvested through human history, but only about a dozen are still economically important today as crops or garden vegetables.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Many *Allium* species and hybrids are cultivated as ornamentals.
[src:allium-validum/allium] These include *A. cristophii* and *A. giganteum*, which are used as border plants for their ornamental flowers, and their "architectural" qualities.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Several hybrids have been bred, or selected, with rich purple flowers.
[src:allium-validum/allium] *A. hollandicum* 'Purple Sensation' is one of the most popular and has been given an Award of Garden Merit (H4).
[src:allium-validum/allium] These ornamental onions produce spherical umbels on single stalks in spring and summer, in a wide variety of sizes and colours, ranging from white (*Allium* 'Mont Blanc'), blue (*A. caeruleum*), to yellow (*A. flavum*) and purple (*A. giganteum*).
[src:allium-validum/allium] By contrast, other species (such as invasive *A. triquetrum* and *A. ursinum*) can become troublesome garden weeds.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Dogs and cats are very susceptible to poisoning after the consumption of certain species.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Cattle have occasionally suffered onion toxicosis as well.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Vegetables of the *Allium* genus can cause digestive disorders for human beings.
[src:allium-validum/allium] The genus includes many economically important species.
[src:allium-validum/allium] These include onions (*A. cepa*), French shallots (*A. oschaninii*), leeks (*A. ampeloprasum*), garlic (*A. sativum*), and herbs such as scallions (various *Allium* species) and chives (*A. schoenoprasum*).
[src:allium-validum/allium] Some have been used as traditional medicines.
[src:allium-validum/allium] Members of the genus and plants with similar properties, referred to in this context as 'leeks', had a prominent role in Germanic paganism.
[src:allium-validum/allium] This includes writing the word *laukaz* ('leek') in runic inscriptions, likely for protection and healing.
[src:allium-validum/allium] This genus also includes species that are abundantly gathered from the wild such as wild garlic (*Allium ursinum*) in Europe and ramps (*Allium tricoccum*) in North America.
